    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your car's alternator is like a tiny, electric-powered generator that sits on the engine and constantly pumps electricity into your car's battery and electrical system, keeping everything from your lights to your radio running while the engine is on. If your alternator is going bad, you might notice the lights dimming or flickering when you're idling, the battery warning light on the dashboard lighting up, or the car struggling to start because the battery isn't getting a charge. To fix this, you'll likely need to have a mechanic test your charging system with a multimeter to ensure the alternator is producing the proper voltage, usually around 13.5 to 14.5 volts. If the voltage is too low, it's time to replace the alternator or the battery, depending on the diagnosis.",
